Feature: Reusable QR + WhatsApp Ordering System for Small Indian Businesses

Build a mobile-first digital ordering web app that can be reused for multiple small businesses such as restaurants, cafes, kirana stores, sweet shops, food stalls, and takeaway counters.

The goal is to create one reusable template system that can be configured quickly for each new business with minimal code changes.

The end users are:
1. Customers who scan a QR code and place an order from mobile.
2. Shop owners who receive orders on WhatsApp and manage menu data from Google Sheets.
3. The service provider/developer who replicates the same system for multiple clients.

BUSINESS OBJECTIVE

Small businesses in India need a simple digital menu and ordering system without installing apps, using complicated software, or learning technical tools. The system should allow customers to scan a QR code, view menu items, add items to cart, enter name and phone number, and place an order. The shop owner should instantly receive the order on WhatsApp.

The system must be reusable so the same codebase can be sold to many businesses with small configuration changes.

MVP SCOPE

The MVP must include:

1. Digital Menu Website
- Mobile-first design.
- Business logo/name/header.
- Categories such as Starters, Main Course, Drinks, Sweets, Snacks, Grocery, etc.
- Items with name, price, description, image, category, availability, and veg/non-veg/type indicator where applicable.
- Search item functionality.
- Simple UI similar to Swiggy/Zomato menu layout.
- Menu data editable via Google Sheets, with sample config/mock data used during local MVP development if Sheets integration is not ready.

2. QR Code Support
- Each business has a unique menu URL.
- Each table can have a unique QR URL using table number query parameter.
- Example: /menu/cafe-99?table=5
- Kirana/sweet shop can use shop-level QR without table.
- QR should open the correct business menu.

3. Cart and Checkout
- Customer can add/remove items.
- Customer can increase/decrease quantity.
- Cart shows item names, quantity, subtotal, and total.
- Checkout captures customer name and phone number.
- No login required.
- Order placement must show success screen with order ID.

4. Order Storage
- Store every order in Google Sheets.
- Required order fields:
  - orderId
  - dateTime
  - businessId
  - businessName
  - tableNo
  - customerName
  - customerPhone
  - itemsJson
  - totalAmount
  - status
  - paymentStatus
  - source

5. Customer Storage
- Store or update customer details in Google Sheets.
- Required customer fields:
  - customerPhone
  - customerName
  - firstOrderDate
  - lastOrderDate
  - totalOrders
  - totalSpend
  - optInWhatsApp
  - lastMessageSent

6. WhatsApp Owner Notification
- When an order is placed, the shop owner must receive a WhatsApp message.
- Message must include:
  - Order ID
  - Customer name
  - Customer phone
  - Table number if available
  - Items with quantity
  - Total amount
- Use official WhatsApp API provider only.
- Implement provider abstraction and placeholder integration so the app builds even if real credentials are missing.
- SMS backup can be planned but not mandatory for MVP implementation.

7. Post-Order Customer Message
- Send thank-you WhatsApp message to customer if legally allowed and configured.
- Include order ID and business name.
- Review link message can be supported as optional automation.

8. Review Request Automation
- Support Google review link in business settings.
- After order completion or after manual trigger, system can send review request message.

9. Marketing Automation Readiness
- Design data model to support future inactive-customer campaigns.
- Future trigger: if customer has not ordered for 15–20 days, send offer message.
- Future trigger: festival/weekend offer messages.
- Must include opt-in and opt-out considerations.

10. Replication for Multiple Businesses
- System must support multiple businesses using config.
- Business-specific data should be kept in config and Google Sheets.
- New business setup should not require rewriting components.

PRIMARY USER STORIES

User Story 1: Customer scans QR
As a customer, I want to scan a QR code and open the correct shop/table menu so that I can place an order without asking for a physical menu.

Acceptance Criteria:
- QR URL opens the correct business menu.
- If table number is present in URL, it is captured automatically.
- If business is inactive or invalid, show a friendly error.

User Story 2: Customer browses menu
As a customer, I want to browse menu items by category so that I can quickly find what I want.

Acceptance Criteria:
- Categories are visible as tabs.
- Items appear under selected category.
- Search filters items by name.
- Unavailable items cannot be added.

User Story 3: Customer uses cart
As a customer, I want to add, remove, and change item quantities so that I can prepare my order.

Acceptance Criteria:
- Add button adds item to cart.
- Plus/minus changes quantity.
- Total amount updates instantly.
- Cart persists while browsing same session.

User Story 4: Customer places order
As a customer, I want to enter my name and phone number and place the order without login.

Acceptance Criteria:
- Name is required.
- Phone number is required.
- Phone number must be validated for Indian mobile format.
- Empty cart cannot be submitted.
- Success screen shows order ID.

User Story 5: Owner receives order
As a shop owner, I want to receive order details on WhatsApp so that I can prepare the order quickly.

Acceptance Criteria:
- Owner receives order alert after successful order save.
- Alert contains customer details, items, quantities, and total.
- If WhatsApp fails, order remains saved.

User Story 6: Developer replicates system
As the developer/service provider, I want to configure a new business quickly so that I can sell the same template to many clients.

Acceptance Criteria:
- Business settings are config-driven.
- New business can be added by adding config and Google Sheet.
- QR URLs can be generated for shop/table.
- No component rewrite needed for each client.

OUT OF SCOPE FOR MVP

- Online payment
- Customer login
- Shop owner admin login
- Full inventory management
- Delivery rider tracking
- Loyalty wallet
- Advanced analytics dashboard
- AI chatbot
- Multi-branch enterprise management
- Complex role-based permissions

CLARIFICATIONS

- Business model: reusable template system for multiple small businesses, not a full SaaS platform in MVP.
- Primary business types: restaurants, cafes, kirana stores, sweet shops, takeaway counters, and food stalls.
- Customer flow: QR scan → menu opens → select items → cart → enter name + phone → place order → success screen.
- Order mode: support both table-based dine-in ordering and shop-level takeaway ordering.
  - If `table` query parameter exists, capture table number.
  - If `table` query parameter does not exist, treat as shop/takeaway order.
- Login: no customer login; no shop-owner login in MVP.
- Payment: no online payment in MVP; payment status defaults to Unpaid or Pay at Counter.
- Backend: use Google Apps Script Web App as API backend.
- Database: use Google Sheets as MVP database with tabs: BusinessSettings, Categories, MenuItems, Orders, Customers, MarketingLog.
- WhatsApp: use official WhatsApp Business API provider only; owner notification is mandatory; customer thank-you and review request are optional but designed.
- SMS: SMS backup is optional and can be planned for later.
- Admin: shop owner edits menu in Google Sheets; no separate admin panel in MVP.
- Multi-business support: use business slug and config-driven setup. Example URL: `/menu/cafe-99?table=5`.
- Hosting: use Vercel, Firebase Hosting, or Netlify, preferring the easiest deployment.
- UI: mobile-first, simple Swiggy/Zomato-like layout.
- Reliability: order must be saved first; WhatsApp failure must not delete or block saved order.
- Security: no API secrets in frontend; WhatsApp tokens remain server-side in Apps Script or provider dashboard.
- Privacy: collect only name and phone number for MVP.
- Replication: new client setup requires only copy Google Sheet template, fill settings/categories/items, add business config, generate QR code, test order, go live.

DEFAULT ASSUMPTIONS

- MVP uses React + Vite frontend.
- MVP uses Google Sheets as database.
- MVP uses Google Apps Script as backend API.
- MVP uses official WhatsApp API provider such as WATI, Interakt, Twilio, Gupshup, or AiSensy.
- Hosting can be Vercel, Firebase Hosting, or Netlify.
- Images are stored as public URLs.
- Menu editing is done directly in Google Sheets.
- Order mode defaults to dine-in/table QR and takeaway/shop QR.
- Default order status is New.
- Payment status defaults to Unpaid.
- Use two sample businesses in config: `cafe-99` and `sharma-sweets`.
- Do not use Firestore for MVP; leave Firebase only for hosting if needed.
- Use placeholder Apps Script property variables for WhatsApp provider tokens and credentials.

Do not ask too many questions. Use these MVP assumptions unless something is truly blocking.
